data.content:
Use `Assert.ThrowsException` (MSTest) or `Assert.Throws` (xUnit/NUnit) instead — it's more precise and doesn't pass if the wrong line throws:

```csharp
[TestMethod]
public void CreateUser_NullEmail_ThrowsException()
{
    var service = new UserService();

    Assert.ThrowsException<ArgumentNullException>(
        () => service.CreateUser(null, "John"));
}
```

**Why:** `[ExpectedException]` catches exceptions from *any* line in the test (including the arrange step), masking bugs. `Assert.ThrowsException` scopes the assertion to the exact call. You can also capture the exception to assert on its message:

```csharp
var ex = Assert.ThrowsException<ArgumentNullException>(
    () => service.CreateUser(null, "John"));
Assert.AreEqual("email", ex.ParamName);
```
